gw.api.rest.validation

Interface JsonPropertyValidator


  • public interface JsonPropertyValidator
    A JsonPropertyValidator represents a validator that executes either for an individual property within a json object or for an element within a json array.

    • Method Summary

      All Methods Instance Methods Abstract Methods 
      Modifier and Type Method and Description
      void validate(java.lang.Object value, JsonObject containingObject, JsonValidatorContext validatorContext)
      Called to validate the given value.

    • Method Detail

      • validate

        void validate(java.lang.Object value,
              JsonObject containingObject,
              JsonValidatorContext validatorContext)
        Called to validate the given value. Validation failures should be reported by calling the appropriate method on the JsonValidatorContext object provided. This method should *not* throw exceptions. Custom property validators will always be executed for a given property, even if the property is not present in the input, allowing them to be used to validate things like conditionally-required properties. The validators will not be invoked, however, if the property's value fails to deserialize (i.e. if the property should be a json string and is specified as an array, or if the property should deserialize to a Date but isn't correctly formatted). Custom property validators are invoked after the containing object is completely deserialized and after default values are set on the object.
        Parameters:
        value - the value to validate, which may be null if the value failed to deserialize properly, wasn't present in the containing object, or was explicitly set to null
        containingObject - the JsonObject that ultimately contains this value, either directly on the object or within a list that is on the object; the object will be fully deserialized, so sibling properties and child properties can be inspected
        validatorContext - the JsonValidatorContext used to report any validation errors
